To indicate italics in most formats (like Markdown, many game engines, or dialogue systems), you
wrap the text in either:

* **Asterisks**: `*italicized text*`
* **Underscores**: `_italicized text_`

Both will render as *italicized text* depending on the system. If you're writing in Python and using
a custom story engine, it depends on how your engine parses formatting. If you're using Markdown or
a Markdown-like parser, asterisks are usually safest.

python def apply\_tone\_to\_remnants(npc\_profile, tone\_effects): """ npc\_profile: dict of
REMNANTS traits for one NPC tone\_effects: dict of TONE changes, e.g. {"empathy": 0.2, "trust":

\["resolve"\] } }

\# Temperament decorators: stylistic wrappers temperaments \= { "Ravi": lambda text: f"{text},
spoken with merchant warmth.", "Nima": lambda text: f"{text} â€” always watching, always wary.",
"Kaelen": lambda text: f"{text}... said with a sly grin.", "Tovren": lambda text: f"{text},

"Drossel": lambda text: f"{text}, mon cher â€” but shadows linger." }

def generate\_dialogue(npc, context="neutral"): name \= npc.name remnants \= npc.remnants

\# Example logic: pick lexicon based on dominant trait dominant\_trait, value \=
max(remnants.items(), key=lambda x: x\[1\])

\# Map trait to lexicon keys if name in lexicons: if dominant\_trait in \["empathy", "trust",
"resolve", "authority", "memory", "nuance", "skepticism"\]: key \= f"{dominant\_trait}\_high" if
value \> 0.7 else f"{dominant\_trait}\_low" if key in lexicons\[name\]: word \=
random.choice(lexicons\[name\]\[key\]) base\_text \= f"My {dominant\_trait} feels {word}" else:
base\_text \= f"My {dominant\_trait} guides me ({value:.2f})" else: base\_text \= f"My
{dominant\_trait} guides me ({value:.2f})" else: base\_text \= f"{name} speaks plainly."

return temperaments.get(name, lambda t: t)(base\_text)
